semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
\label{l:quantifier free type} Let $\lang$ be a language and $T$ a theory on $\lang$. Let $\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}$ be the relational reduct, i.e. the reduct consisting on the relation symbols of $\lang$. Assume that for every function symbol of $\lang$, there is a formula in $\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}$ defining it in $T$. Let $a$ and $b$ enumerate two models of $T$. Then, $\qftp_{\lang}(a)=\qftp_{\lang}(b)$ if and only if $\qftp_{\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}}(a)=\qftp_{\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}}(b)$. In other words, every $\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}${\hyp}isomorphism between two models of $T$ is an $\lang${\hyp}isomorphism.
\begin{proof}
Note that, by the hypotheses, any $\lang_{\mathrm{rel}}${\hyp}isomorphism of $T${\hyp}models is an $\lang${\hyp}isomorphism.
\end{proof}

