\label{l:cones and cone independence} Let $T$ be a meet{\hyp}tree, $\gamma$ a point and $A,B,C$ subsets of $T$ such that $A\indepe[\gamma]{C}B$. Then, $\cone_\gamma(AC)\cap \cone_\gamma(BC)=\cone_\gamma(C)$.
\begin{proof} It is enough to show that if $a\in A$ and $b\in B$ such that $a\in\cone_\gamma(b)$, then $a\in\cone_\gamma(C)$. As $A\indepe[\gamma]{C}B$, either $a\meet b\in\langle C\rangle_\gamma$ or there is $c\in \langle C\rangle_\gamma$ such that $a\meet c\neq b\meet c$. In the first case, $a\meet b\in\langle C\rangle_\gamma$ and $a\in\cone_\gamma(a\meet b)$. In the second case, by \cref{l:three elements}, $\gamma<a\meet b=a\meet b\meet c\leq a\meet c$, so $a\in\cone_\gamma(c)$.
\end{proof}

